48th Street, west from but not including Fifth Avenue. This view shows the street before big business lofts were started there.

1925.

16-72 West 48th Street, south side, west from Fifth to Sixth Aves., showing prominently the newly erected Winston Building, that will be known as No. 22. The 1934 R.E. Atlas gives the same as the National Jewel's Board of Trade. According to the N.Y. Times of October 31, 1937 the 2 structures (No. 18 and 20), adjacent to the east side of the aforementioned building, will be demolished and their site utilized for a 2-story building to be occupied by B. Westermann Co. No. 18 is the old Rhinelander home and appears on the left. For further data upon same, see the periodical mentioned.

Peyser and Patzig.

Fifth Avenue at S.E. corner of 48th Street.

February 22, 1931.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.

This is the Robert W. Goelet House. For additional data see the "Herald-Tribune," January 4, 1942.

Fifth Avenue (right of No. 1), north from W. 48th Street (foreground of No. 2, thoroughfare not seen), showing the Rockefeller Center (then known as Radio City) site and vicinity. The clearance seen is between 49th and 50th Streets and is today (1938) the Plaza and Sunken Fountain site. To the left, where buildings are partially demolished, stands the 70 storied R.C.A. Building. Subsequently the block to the north was razed for the present sites of the International, the Associated Press, the R.E.O. Buildings and the International Music Hall. The photographer is apparently atop the Ampico Tower Building (No. 584-Fifth Avenue) and viewing northward to Central Park.

In the lower right corner of No. 2 appears the upper portions of the almost completed Goelet Building (No. 608-Fifth Avenue) at the S.W. corner of W. 49th Street. This structure was completed early in 1931.

Rockefeller Center, New York
February 12, 1975

For more than four decades, the elegant Rainbow Room and Rainbow Grill located 65 floors above midtown. Manhattan in Rockefeller Center have been New York City's most talked about restaurant and nighclub [sic] with outstanding entertainment and top cuisine plus an unexcelled view of the Manhattan skyline.

Opened to the public as a formal skyscraper supper club in 1934, the Rainbow Room, above two stories in height, occupies the entire eastern end of the RCA Building's 65th floor. Its 24 floor-to-ceiling windows line the north and south sides of the spacious dining room permitting breathtaking views of Manhattan island and surrounding areas for 50 miles. Panels between the windows are covered with plum colored silk tafetta, complimented by gold draperies and emerald green carpeting. The tables are set on three levels beneath a magnificent crystal chandelier of classic design.

Cocktails and dining ar [sic] offered nightly, seven days a week. Brunch is served from 11:30 a.m. to 3 p.m. Saturday and Sunday.
